text: LOL. Okay, let's do this.  - 1) San Andreas is a strike-slip transform fault.  It moves side-to-side, not apart.  The worst the Rock would have to face is a 10 meter off road excursion in his fancy, product-placed pickup truck. - 2) The Pacific Plate is the one pushing up, meaning that LA wouldn't fall a few feet, it would rise a few feet. - 3) LA will not rise a few feet -- it would move north a few feet. - 4) Yes, the destruction of the cherished Hollywood sign is the scariest thing the Rock could witness -- unless you live near the sign in which case you're probably thrilled because now the tourists won't be traipsing through your yard anymore.  That is, of course, until someone -- you know -- stands the letters back up. - 5) Technically, any earthquake larger than a 7.0 can be felt around the world -- including the "East Coast". - 6) It is IMPOSSIBLE for an earthquake to cause a center-bulge failure in an arch-gravity dam. - 7) 1:35 - Everybody down. Really? Why? To avoid the... shaking ground? Falling buildings? The flames of Godzilla? - 8) #WhereWillYouBe? Probably not in a theater.

text: The Richter scale is a magnitude if 1.0 is 10. 2.0 is 100. 7.0 would be 10^7. At that point major structures buckle and fail. since records have been kept. There has never been a 10.0 EVER on Earth. It is known the San Andreas Fault is long overdue for its next earthquake. Ask any Geologist, who isn't trying to just scare or placate you, but tell you like it is, they are literally taking bets it will be over 9.0 and how far.  Even modern structures in California today will fail because quite simply the topology of the state will change enormously. The seeming unreality of the land behaving like water is VERY possible. Just as Japan. It is however extremely unlikely Califiornia will slide into the sea. That simply is NOT how the geology of Earth works.  The part about the East Coast feeling the earthquake is not unfounded. But again it does not seem likely the San Andreas quake itself will cause any real damage beyond Arizona, Nevada, and Oregon and other directly adjoining states. Hawaii is going to have to brace for a HUGE Tsunami. But just as problematic is the North American Continent is riddled with faults. Many of these faults are considerd or known to be geologically active, that is they are building up to a large quake themselves.  It is known even a small quake can excite other, relatively nearby, faults into releasing their quakes. It is very possible the so-called "big one" could cause continent wide earthquakes ranging from very minor 1.0 to major 6.0 or higher quakes.  As absurd as "2012", which was no holds barred an absurd movie (spoiler: the Earth literally tries to turn itself inside out and the only way to survive it is to escape to space. No I have NOT seen it.), San Andreas is actually more worrying even scary because it literally could happen tomorrow. Sorry, if you want to dig on the movie because it makes you feel somehow superior, and it probably is "not good", but this sort of movie makes me very curious about what really is and could really happen.  Frankly, the idea is more exciting, scary, and enthusing, than the movie is likely to be.

text: Man......I'm really getting sick of these effects heavy smash fests. Don't get me wrong it's fun to catch these every now and then--but it really seems like this is all Hollywood is churning out in recent years. When you watch it for literally the hundredth time in a row it really gets charmless and numbing.   I've always been a big fan of the cinema for a while now but in recent years I have increasingly found my self (surprisingly, for me) transitioning to the small screen (shows on HBO, Netflix, BBC etc.) and (gasp!) books. I find the simple pleasure of enjoying a good story more riveting than an endless cascade of fireworks. Ironic, since that was what originally attracted me to the cinema in the first place. Changing times, and to each their own I suppose.

Sure there are pretty graphics in this film to make it look interesting but the number of potential dead from such an earth quake is no illusion. If a small Island like Haiti can suffer  more than a quarter of a million dead what will happen to the densely populated areas of California?  *There will be famines and earthquakes in many parts of the world.  But all this is only the first of the birth pains, with MORE to come.* Matthew 24.7  *What preparation we provide for natural disasters will mean nothing if we have not prepared for the coming of Christ. text: 1) The San Andreas does not run under, or even that close to, downtown LA.   (Of course, that does not preclude damage to downtown, mainly from other faults that may "sympathetically" blow if the earthquake on the San Andreas is strong enough, but it means the damage ON the San Andreas will not DIRECTLY cause that damage) 2) Many of the buildings in downtown were either built to the tougher standards enacted in the 1970s, or retrofitted.  (Of course, that doesn't mean they can't be earthquake-damaged.) 3) The San Andreas fault line itself is not capable of producing more than an high 7 or 8 earthquake; while this sounds high, and it is, it is not the 9.5 or 10 that is generally depicted in disaster films. 4) The Richter scale rating and the damage are determined by how much of the fault blows, not how much shaking there is.  There is another scale for that.  In the disaster scenarios they predict for the Cascadia Subduction Zone (N. Cal up to Vancouver, BC, including Portland and Seattle), they routinely predict a mag 9 earthquake.  Why? Because they predict practically the ENTIRE subduction zone to blow, which means that the ENTIRE fault running from N. Cal to north of Vancouver, BC will blow.  There are plenty of videos you can watch on YT to get an idea of this.  Look for "Cascadia Subduction Zone".  The last major earthquake on that fault WAS a 9.0, and it hit on Jan 26, 1700.  They have studied this fault line intensively, and it involves the Juan de Fuca tectonic plate.  Because that plate is small by geologic standards, it is easier for the entire thing to blow.  The studies they've done have determined that the AVERAGE length of time between eruptions is around 300 years, so technically, we are overdue.  IMHO in terms of geological time, 300 years isn't much.  We are also way overdue for the southern branch of the San Andreas to blow, and the concern is mainly from Palm Springs to Riverside, under which the fault line runs DIRECTLY.  I remember one time we were in Palm Springs and the San Andreas DID blow, but it was a very small earthquake (around 4)  So keep in mind how much of "San Andreas" is fact and how much is theatrics, hysterics, and how much is marketing.

The Qur'an made a few but they're vague and some turned out to be false. The Bible has a 100% accuracy track record when it comes to prophecy and future events).  This all means that Christ is about to return, whether you believe it or not. Which is great if you're saved but it'll be hell on earth if you aren't. They're even beheading people here in the U.S.   When we combine current events with the fact that ISIS controls 1/3 of Syria, and many terrorist organizations have a base in its city of Damascus, it appears evident that we will soon see the fulfillment of Isaiah 17.  (Thanks C.N. for this listing!)  We're going to see all prophecy be fulfilled soon! People! Wake up! You can watch real-world news and see these prophecies coming to a head! The writing is on the wall. The Bible isn't a bunch of fairy stories. Archeology,  geology, and even topography confirm these people, places, and events existed and happened! Only God knows and can prophecy the future thousands of years in advance.  Given that prophecy is coming true 100%, did you know the Bible also states that Jesus will soon reign over the earth for 1000 years? We can rest assured that the earth is going to stick around. The dangerous weather we're all seeing is actually called birth pangs, not climate change. Turbulent, violent weather is a major prophetic indicator. The earth itself is screaming at us that Christ is about to return! That's why creation is in such an uproar.  I'm telling you the truth: Krishna won't save you. allah's just an amalgamation of all of islam's different gods rolled into one. And being a good person won't save you (we've all sinned in some capacity in our lives- how many people have you cussed at and belittled by trolling online this week?).   But guess what? God LOVES you! Goodness does He love you. It goes beyond anything you could understand. And He knows every jot of information there is to know about you, the good and the bad. And guess what else? He loves you... even though you shop-lifted that one time. He loves you even though you get a sick thrill out of trolling people or watching japanese hentai. He loves you even though you're struggling with heroin. And He doesn't want you to suffer under the idea that you did something that you assume is unforgivable. He loves you even though you've slandered and hurt others. And He'll forgive anything. For instance, people have burned His Word. Yet, He's forgiven them! And He wants to forgive you and help you get out of your sinful lifestyle! It doesn't matter if you're black, white, asian, or indian. Ethnicity isn't a barrier to Him. You're His child! We're ALL His children! And if you'll believe in Him, accept Him as your Lord and Savior and repent of your sins, He'll save you! Simple as that. No works or merit-earning required.  Do yourself the biggest favor of your life and take that offer. Why settle for mud pies here on earth when Jesus offers you an eternal feast?  Don't be left behind to endure the Tribulation. Save yourselves now while the Ark doors are still open... because they're about to close. And you do not want to be left here when they finally do close. The judgement of God is a terrifying thing and if you think God is unfair for judging sinners, need I remind you that He's given humanity the opportunity to escape His coming judgement for over 2000 years if they would simply believe in Jesus and repent.  We're talking about the fate of your eternal future here... and eternity is an awful long time to be on the wrong side. Don't let satan drag you down into the lake of fire with him. That's his end game. He doesn't care about you. His attitude is, "If I'm going down, you're going down with me!" He wants to destroy you and as many people as possible. What else can explain the evil you see increasing everywhere on a daily basis? Satan knows his time is short and he wants to cause as much damage and ensnare as many souls as possible- yours included. Don't let that monster win your soul!  If you doubt all this, that's fair. You're allowed to doubt all of this if you want to. But the writing is on the wall every day in the news. It's getting harder and harder to deny if you'll wake up and be honest with yourself.  If you have doubts but deep down you want to be saved, I encourage you to seek out the following authors. author: J. O.

text: While the movie promises to be a fun disaster flick, its title suggests a scary real-world tie-in. “San Andreas” is likely a reference to the San Andreas Fault line, which cuts The Golden State in two. The sliding land boundary separates the state into the Pacific plate and the North American Plate. According to Geology.com, the fault line runs thorough many populated areas of California and accounts for many of its earthquakes. The plates shift only a couple inches a year, roughly the rate at which human fingernails grow. However, these shifting rates are only an average – theoretically there’s nothing stopping a catastrophic shift in the fault line. While it’s likely that the film plays a little fast and loose with the science behind the San Andreas Fault line, it’s at least sound in concept.

author: 22kinkykinky

text: For those who think this is not gonna happen:  Look up, search "San Andreas Fault Lines" and you will see how retarted you all are for commenting "This is like 2012 movie, which is not gonna happen too." The most recent San Andreas earthquake was in 1908. Even though it only causes 1 fatality, it causes huge devastation of San Andreas. That's why Golden State splits into half. Scientists predict that if it moved, it will cause 9.0 magnitude earthquake through the Richter Scale and cause huge tsunamis. Because San Andreas is included in the Pacific's Ring of Fire. Where the tectonic plates split into half. But anytime now, IT WILL SURELY MOVE. That's all the facts i can give of. God, out of 100 commenters on youtube only 2 commenters use their brain.

Американцы более верующие внешне люди, а в Библии говорится, что не надо в голове держать плохие мысли. А кино это? Кино это что? Разве это не плохие мысли, которые навязывают всем людям. Один негатив... Мало было американцам башен-близнецов. Еще хотят катастроф для себя. Так и будут они, пока не научатся снимать кино позитивное и о любви. Любое кино должно быть для души, а не для денег. Это же фильм только для денег.Сейчас начнут цифры всем рассказывать, сколько денег собрало это кино.... Ну детский сад, да и только. Точно говорит наш Задорнов  о наличии ума у американцев. Не хватает мудрости, чтобы отказаться от подобных фильмов.

text: The shot of the city of LA rolling up and down like slow ocean rollers is pretty much what people described during the 1906 earthquake. Ground displacement then was around 6 meters. Today the fault has some 7 meters stored up, and when it goes its far from certain that's all it will move. It may well snap beyond that "break-even" point, which would mean a much bigger quake than in 1906. Hollywood should make a movie about what really might actually happen some day. Guaranteed it'd be a lot more exciting and scary than this cartoon fantasy. A lot more scary. Because in truth it's not a "might", it's a "when."

text: The big one is coming for real. I live in So Cal in Orange County CA and we had a earthquake about a year ago. Was only 3.5 but because it was almost at the surface it was more like a 6.5. No wave or rolls,  just hard jolts that damaged my house along with surrounding houses. It felt like someone picked up the house and shaked it violently. The after shocks continued for about a week. Every 20 minutes the house would just jolt, like someone was smacking it. Turns out it is on a major fault line that goes all the way to Santa Monica. They are predicting that if it happens to be a large 6 plus earthquake on this fault, it will do catastrophic damage from orange county all the way through LA county to the ocean. I seriously want to move.

text: The San Andreas Fault Zone is a Right Lateral Strike slip fault. Its a transform boundary and as such grinds parallel to either side.. IT DOES NOT PULL APART AND CREATE GIANT CITY SWALLOWING HOLES. NOR does it create massive tidal waves that envelope the SF Bay. the only accurate things i see in this movie are the waves caused by earthquakes ( though those are exaggerated too) and the amount of destruction possible in a magnitude 9 earthquake. though even that seems a bit exaggerated as its LAW in california to earthquake proof buildings near a fault. and BTW, its IMPOSSIBLE for the same earthquake on the san andreas to effect both North and Southern California. theres a creeping section of the fault that runs from SLO to Monterey that acts as a buffer between the northern and southern sections of the fault.....stupid ass movie.

text: http://screenrant.com/san-andreas-trailer-dwayne-johnson/  The new trailer for San Andreas tries to add a little more gravity to the situation with the foreboding question of “Where will you be?” (actually that’s #WhereWillYouBe), a repeated excerpt of a moody cover song and a dark prediction from Paul Giamatti’s character, but it’s clear that a lot of this movie’s appeal is going to be in its money shots of entire cities rippling, dams bursting, and Johnson flying helicopters past collapsing buildings.  San Andreas is, of course, named after the San Andreas Fault, a meeting of two tectonic plates that extends for over 800 miles through California, and which has already caused a great number of earthquakes since records began. The current research suggests that a major earthquake (over 7.0 on the Richter scale and referred to in predictions as “The Big One”) could occur at any time; and if it happens between now and the release of San Andreas, then the movie could become very tasteless, very fast.

text: My friends and I joked about this SO MUCH when we saw the trailer...I knew what it was so I turned to my friend and said "Where's CJ?"...then the title came up and he cracked up and I said "I need this more than you...I THINK!?" (when CJ steals cars). BTW this looks like pure shit. I like The Rock, but c'mon Hollywood, what is your obsession with mass destruction and scores of people dying horrible deaths in the wake of a disaster. I mean over 8,000 people JUST lost their lives from the Nepal earthquakes..now I know the studio didn't exactly EXPECT that to happen right before the release of this "movie"..but couldn't they have the decency to delay the movie atleast a few months? I mean even Training Day got pushed because of 9/11 because of it's violence, and that had absolutely nothing to do with terrorists. I mean EVEN SPIDER-MAN removed the trailer they had of the World Trade Center, and took out the scene...Hollywood these days just don't give a shit I guess.  All I know is...even if that earthquake didn't just happen, it DOES NOT make for a good movie, unless you are so stupid that you need to just watch a bunch of loud crazy nonsense happening all at once to be entertained. That's what Michael Bay movies are for.  Yeah...I hope Mad Max: Fury Road stays #1 at the Box Office and keeps this OUT of the #1 spot. This movie and Jurrassic World look awful. Both just loaded to the brim with CGI...and just an excuse to see people get killed like crazy. Atleast the violence in Mad Max: Fury Road will be stylized, exhilerating, breathtaking, and a hyper-active fantasy driven car chase down Fury Road...not HEY lets make a sequel to a franchise that should have STAYED left alone, but we fucked up twice already so why not throw in a 4th movie? or HEY I got an idea...lets watch people die from natural disasters and make you think how hundreds of people are crying over their lost loved ones, as we in America sit with a bucket of popcorn and applaud at how horrific San Andreas' natural disasters can be. YES!!! lets watch people die just like how they die in real life!!! YES!!! Rated PG-13.

text: Are there any other structural engineers out there who are as sick as I am of seeing Californian reinforced concrete buildings, designed to fail in a "ductile" manner during an earthquake, crumbling and shattering as if they were made of icing sugar?  Why doesn't Hollywood spend more time showing what real structural failure looks like, or informing the public about the theory and benefits of Ductile Overcapacity Design and the formation and limited propagation of plastic hinges throughout the load resisting frame or shear wall system (absorbing the seismic energy, but avoiding TOTAL collapse)?  I'm sure that if the first, say, 45 minutes of the film was devoted to an introductory primer on the current theory of structural design for earthquake, touching on how this is implemented in current American design codes, such as ACI-318, followed by 20 questions that all must complete before the film can be shown, everybody would be happy?   Or perhaps not.    Maybe this is why Hollywood directors and writers pull down such huge earnings while engineers like me are doomed to sit at home each night in beer and pizza stained tee-shirts, trolling YouTube and wondering why we've got no friends at all.  This could be why all conversation stops and everybody clears the room when I walk in, saying that they've just remembered that their house is on fire.  :-(   :-(

text: "You will feel it on the East coast"?  LOL NO.  Look, I live in California.  A quake here big enough to cause damage that far away would have to be on the scale of the rupturing of the Earth's crust.  That doesn't and cannot happen with earthquakes.  You need something like "impact by an asteroid the size of Detroit" to do that.  Also, that giant fissure in the ground -- that doesn't happen either, even with a big quake.  That's not how it works.  The shot of the ripple effect spreading across the ground, though, is pretty cool and that's probably accurate.
author: Anne Haight
